<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900411-0078</DOCNO><DOCID>900411-0078.</DOCID><HL>   International Paper   Says Profit Fell 19%   During First Quarter</HL><DATE>04/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   IP</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)PULP, PAPER, PACKAGING (ALL TYPES) (PUL)</IN><LP>   PURCHASE, N.Y. -- International Paper Co. posted a 19%decline in net income for the first quarter despite a 23%rise in sales, blaming the drop on high capital spending andlow prices for some products.   The maker of paper and pulp products, which declined toforecast 1990 results, may face further pressure this year asit proceeds with a planned $1.1 billion in capital spendingto improve plants and equipment this year.</LP><TEXT>   International Paper said first-quarter net fell to $180million, or $1.65 a share, from $223 million, or $1.96 ashare, a year earlier. Sales rose to $3.2 billion from $2.6billion. The company attributed the decline to lower pricesfor paper pulps and printing paper that it sells.International Paper also cited a slightly higher tax rateoverall because of rates in foreign markets and in somestates, and manufacturing delays caused by bad weather andplant construction.   John A. Georges, chairman and chief executive officer,said the most significant first-quarter price declines werefor uncoated printing and writing papers. He said that&quot;recent increases in industry capacity led to pricereductions even though sales volume remained at healthylevels.&quot; Price increases effective April 1 indicate animproved supply-demand balance, the company said.   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,International Paper rose 62.5 cents to $52.125.</TEXT></DOC>